{
  "answer": "In Cynewulf's *Elene* (Chapter 1), Elene (Helena) arrives in Jerusalem and summons the wisest Jews—first 3,000 learned in Mosaic law—to interrogate them about Christ and implicitly the Cross (referred to as the \"victory-beacon\" or \"holy tree,\" i.e., the True Cross). She accuses them of rejecting and killing the prophesied Messiah.[^1] They consult and return with 1,000 more experts; Elene presses them further by quoting prophets (Moses, David, Isaiah) foretelling Christ's birth and their rejection of him, demanding answers from their law.[^2] She sends for yet another group of 500; they deny knowledge of Christ, prompting her threat of fiery death if they persist in lying. They then hand over Judas as their wisest, whom Elene takes as hostage and interrogates privately about the Cross's location, threatening death and eventually starving him until he reveals Calvary.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [p-7b1c1f](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-7b1c1f).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [p-f5d1f1](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [p-534627](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-534627); [p-f5d1f1](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).",
